# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} For a very low price; very [[cheaply]].
#* '''1919''', [[w:William Somerset Maugham|W. Somerset Maugham]], ''[[w:The Moon and Sixpence|The Moon and Sixpence]]'', [[s:The Moon and Sixpence/Chapter XLVIII|chapter 48]]:
#*: They remembered then that they could have bought '''for a song''' canvases which now were worth large sums.
#* '''2009''' Dec. 11, "[http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/dec2009/gb20091211_682799.htm Jet Cemetery: Where Airplanes Go to Die]," ''Businessweek'' <small>(retrieved 6 April 2015)</small>:
#*: [T]he contents of aircraft that once commanded prices up to $148m are now being sold off '''for a song''' after being torn apart in Gloucestershire's aviation charnel house.
#* '''2011''', {{w|Kat Martin}}, ''A Song for My Mother'', Vanguard Press, {{ISBN|9781593156565}}, {{gbooks|aDz9AgAAQBAJ|200|for|a|song}}:
#*: In his senior year, he had run across an old '66 Chevy Super Sport headed for the junkyard, bought it '''for a song''', and overhauled it with his dad's help, turning it into the big red muscle car it was back in its day.
#* '''2013''' Aug. 16, Robin Finn, "[http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/18/realestate/a-former-madoff-penthouse-goes-back-on-the-market.html?_r=0 A Former Madoff Penthouse Goes Back on the Market]," ''New York Times'' <small>(retrieved 6 April 2015)</small>:
#*: He bought it '''for a song''' in 1984 compared with what his fellow financiers were spending on tonier Park and Fifth Avenues.

